{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01V2xJwYSfUyRnN79tfER5qi","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Story 7.1: Score-Based Circuit Breaker Module\n2\t\n3\tStatus: verifying\n4\t\n5\t## Story\n6\t\n7\tAs a developer,\n8\tI want a circuit breaker that detects evaluator score stagnation,\n9\tso that the engine halts instead of burning tokens on repeated failing iterations.\n10\t\n11\t## Acceptance Criteria\n12\t\n13\t1. **Given** a new file `src/lib/circuit-breaker.ts` exists\n14\t   **When** inspected\n15\t   **Then** it exports an `evaluateProgress()` function that accepts an array of `EvaluatorScore` entries (from `workflow-state.ts`) and returns a `CircuitBreakerDecision` indicating whether to continue or halt\n16\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n17\t\n18\t2. **Given** evaluator scores across iterations where the `passed` count has not increased for 2+ consecutive iterations\n19\t   **When** `evaluateProgress()` is called\n20\t   **Then** it returns `{ halt: true, reason: 'score-stagnation', ... }` indicating stagnation was detected\n21\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n22\t\n23\t3. **Given** evaluator scores across iterations where the `passed` count increased in the most recent iteration\n24\t   **When** `evaluateProgress()` is called\n25\t   **Then** it returns `{ halt: false }` indicating progress is being made\n26\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n27\t\n28\t4. **Given** fewer than 2 evaluator scores recorded (first iteration or only one score)\n29\t   **When** `evaluateProgress()` is called\n30\t   **Then** it returns `{ halt: false }` because there is insufficient history to detect stagnation\n31\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n32\t\n33\t5. **Given** `evaluateProgress()` returns `{ halt: true }`\n34\t   **When** the result is inspected\n35\t   **Then** it includes `remainingFailures`: the list of AC numbers that still fail, extracted from the most recent score, and `scoreHistory`: the array of `passed` counts across all iterations\n36\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n37\t\n38\t6. **Given** the `CircuitBreakerDecision` type exported from `circuit-breaker.ts`\n39\t   **When** inspected\n40\t   **Then** it is a discriminated union: `{ halt: false }` or `{ halt: true; reason: string; remainingFailures: number[]; scoreHistory: number[] }`\n41\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n42\t\n43\t7. **Given** a score history of realistic size (up to 20 iterations)\n44\t   **When** `evaluateProgress()` is called\n45\t   **Then** it completes in under 5ms (no async operations, pure computation)\n46\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n47\t\n48\t8. **Given** the workflow engine in `workflow-engine.ts`\n49\t   **When** a loop iteration completes and a verdict score has been recorded\n50\t   **Then** the engine calls `evaluateProgress()` from `circuit-breaker.ts` and, if `halt: true`, sets `circuit_breaker.triggered = true`, `circuit_breaker.reason` to the returned reason, and updates `circuit_breaker.score_history` in the workflow state\n51\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n52\t\n53\t9. **Given** unit tests for the circuit breaker module\n54\t   **When** `npm run test:unit` is executed\n55\t   **Then** tests pass at 80%+ coverage for `circuit-breaker.ts` covering: stagnation detection, progress detection, insufficient history, remaining failures extraction, score history reporting, edge cases (all-unknown scores, zero-to-zero stagnation, single AC)\n56\t   <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n57\t\n58\t10. **Given** `npm run build` is executed\n59\t    **When** the build completes\n60\t    **Then** it succeeds with zero errors\n61\t    **And** `npm run test:unit` passes with no regressions in existing test suites\n62\t    <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n63\t\n64\t## Tasks / Subtasks\n65\t\n66\t- [x] Task 1: Create `src/lib/circuit-breaker.ts` with types and `evaluateProgress()` (AC: #1, #2, #3, #4, #5, #6, #7)\n67\t  - [x] Define `CircuitBreakerDecision` discriminated union type\n68\t  - [x] Implement `evaluateProgress(scores: EvaluatorScore[]): CircuitBreakerDecision`\n69\t  - [x] Stagnation rule: halt when `passed` count has not increased for 2+ consecutive iterations\n70\t  - [x] Extract remaining failures from `total - passed` of the latest score\n71\t  - [x] Build `scoreHistory` as `scores.map(s => s.passed)`\n72\t  - [x] Return `{ halt: false }` for fewer than 2 scores\n73\t  - [x] Keep module pure (no I/O, no async, no state mutation)\n74\t\n75\t- [x] Task 2: Integrate `evaluateProgress()` into `workflow-engine.ts` loop block (AC: #8)\n76\t  - [x] Import `evaluateProgress` from `circuit-breaker.ts`\n77\t  - [x] After recording evaluator score in the loop (around line 616), call `evaluateProgress(currentState.evaluator_scores)`\n78\t  - [x] If `halt: true`, update `currentState.circuit_breaker` with `{ triggered: true, reason, score_history: decision.scoreHistory }`\n79\t  - [x] The existing check at line 651 (`if (currentState.circuit_breaker.triggered)`) already handles the halt — no changes needed there\n80\t\n81\t- [x] Task 3: Write unit tests in `src/lib/__tests__/circuit-breaker.test.ts` (AC: #9, #10)\n82\t  - [x] Test: 2+ scores with no improvement triggers halt\n83\t  - [x] Test: improving scores do not trigger halt\n84\t  - [x] Test: fewer than 2 scores returns halt: false\n85\t  - [x] Test: halt decision includes correct remainingFailures\n86\t  - [x] Test: halt decision includes correct scoreHistory\n87\t  - [x] Test: all-unknown scores (passed=0 across iterations) triggers halt\n88\t  - [x] Test: single-AC edge case (passed goes 0, 0 = stagnation)\n89\t  - [x] Test: passed goes 1, 1, 2 = no stagnation (improved on last iteration)\n90\t  - [x] Test: passed goes 1, 2, 2 = stagnation (last two identical)\n91\t  - [x] Test: performance — 20 scores evaluates in <5ms\n92\t  - [x] Verify `npm run build` passes\n93\t  - [x] Verify no regressions in existing tests\n94\t\n95\t## Dev Notes\n96\t\n97\t### Module Design\n98\t\n99\t`circuit-breaker.ts` is a pure computation module — no file I/O, no async, no side effects. It takes evaluator score history and returns a decision. The workflow engine is responsible for calling it and updating state.\n100\t\n101\tThe stagnation detection algorithm is simple: compare the `passed` count of the last N iterations. If the most recent `passed` count is not greater than the one before it (for 2+ consecutive iterations), stagnation is detected. This prevents burning tokens when the dev agent keeps producing the same failing code.\n102\t\n103\t### CircuitBreakerDecision Type\n104\t\n105\t```typescript\n106\texport type CircuitBreakerDecision =\n107\t  | { halt: false }\n108\t  | {\n109\t      halt: true;\n110\t      reason: string;\n111\t      remainingFailures: number[];\n112\t      scoreHistory: number[];\n113\t    };\n114\t```\n115\t\n116\tThe `remainingFailures` field should contain AC indices that are still failing. Since `EvaluatorScore` only has aggregate counts (passed/failed/unknown), not per-AC detail, `remainingFailures` should be derived as a range `[1..total]` minus passed count — or more practically, just report the count of failures. However, the epic says \"remaining failures\" — check if the engine has access to the full `EvaluatorVerdict.findings` to extract specific AC numbers. If not, use the aggregate score.\n117\t\n118\t**Clarification:** The `workflow-engine.ts` currently stores only the aggregate `EvaluatorScore` in state (passed/failed/unknown/total), NOT the per-AC findings. The `EvaluatorVerdict.findings` array is available at verdict parse time but is not persisted to state. For `remainingFailures`, use the aggregate: `total - passed` gives the count, and you can produce an array like `[1, 2, ..., (total-passed)]` as placeholder indices. If the engine later needs specific AC numbers, that's a future enhancement.\n119\t\n120\t### Integration Point in workflow-engine.ts\n121\t\n122\tThe score recording happens at lines 587-616 of `workflow-engine.ts`. After the score is recorded and state is written, insert the circuit breaker evaluation:\n123\t\n124\t```typescript\n125\t// After writeWorkflowState(currentState, projectDir); on line 616\n126\tconst cbDecision = evaluateProgress(currentState.evaluator_scores);\n127\tif (cbDecision.halt) {\n128\t  currentState = {\n129\t    ...currentState,\n130\t    circuit_breaker: {\n131\t      triggered: true,\n132\t      reason: cbDecision.reason,\n133\t      score_history: cbDecision.scoreHistory,\n134\t    },\n135\t  };\n136\t  writeWorkflowState(currentState, projectDir);\n137\t}\n138\t```\n139\t\n140\tThe existing check at line 651 already handles `circuit_breaker.triggered === true` by setting phase to `'circuit-breaker'` and returning.\n141\t\n142\t### Existing Types in workflow-state.ts\n143\t\n144\tThe module already defines the types this story needs:\n145\t\n146\t```typescript\n147\t// Already exists in workflow-state.ts:\n148\texport interface EvaluatorScore {\n149\t  iteration: number;\n150\t  passed: number;\n151\t  failed: number;\n152\t  unknown: number;\n153\t  total: number;\n154\t  timestamp: string;\n155\t}\n156\t\n157\texport interface CircuitBreakerState {\n158\t  triggered: boolean;\n159\t  reason: string | null;\n160\t  score_history: number[];\n161\t}\n162\t```\n163\t\n164\tImport `EvaluatorScore` from `workflow-state.ts`. Do NOT redefine these types.\n165\t\n166\t### Dependencies\n167\t\n168\t- **Imports from:** `workflow-state.ts` (for `EvaluatorScore` type only)\n169\t- **Imported by:** `workflow-engine.ts` (calls `evaluateProgress()`)\n170\t- **No other dependencies.** This is a leaf module.\n171\t\n172\t### File Structure\n173\t\n174\t- New file: `src/lib/circuit-breaker.ts` — the module (~50-80 LOC)\n175\t- New file: `src/lib/__tests__/circuit-breaker.test.ts` — unit tests (~120-180 LOC)\n176\t- Modified file: `src/lib/workflow-engine.ts` — add import and call to `evaluateProgress()` after score recording\n177\t\n178\t### Testing Standards\n179\t\n180\t- Framework: `vitest` (already configured)\n181\t- Pattern: co-located tests in `src/lib/__tests__/`\n182\t- Coverage target: 80%+\n183\t- No mocks needed — `evaluateProgress()` is pure computation\n184\t- Performance test: use `performance.now()` to assert <5ms\n185\t\n186\t### Anti-Patterns to Avoid\n187\t\n188\t- **Do NOT add async to evaluateProgress()** — it's pure synchronous computation\n189\t- **Do NOT read/write workflow-state.yaml from circuit-breaker.ts** — the engine handles state persistence\n190\t- **Do NOT redefine EvaluatorScore or CircuitBreakerState** — import from workflow-state.ts\n191\t- **Do NOT modify the CircuitBreakerState interface** — the existing shape is correct\n192\t- **Do NOT cache state between calls** — each call is independent, receives full score history\n193\t- **Do NOT add the circuit breaker to the module's own state** — the engine manages `WorkflowState`\n194\t- **Do NOT import from evaluator.ts or verdict-parser.ts** — circuit-breaker only needs aggregate scores\n195\t\n196\t### Project Structure Notes\n197\t\n198\t- `src/lib/circuit-breaker.ts` aligns with architecture-v2.md module list (7 core modules)\n199\t- Test file `src/lib/__tests__/circuit-breaker.test.ts` follows co-located test pattern\n200\t- No new directories needed\n201\t- No new dependencies needed\n202\t\n203\t### Previous Story Intelligence\n204\t\n205\tFrom story 6-3 (evaluator prompt template):\n206\t- The evaluator agent now has a full anti-leniency prompt template in `evaluator.yaml`\n207\t- `compileSubagentDefinition()` incorporates `prompt_template` into agent instructions\n208\t- The evaluator produces `EvaluatorVerdict` JSON with per-AC scores\n209\t\n210\tFrom story 6-2 (verdict schema & parsing):\n211\t- `parseVerdict()` in `verdict-parser.ts` returns `EvaluatorVerdict` with `score.passed`, `score.failed`, `score.unknown`, `score.total`\n212\t- `VerdictParseError` with `retryable` flag — retry semantics already in engine\n213\t\n214\tFrom story 5-2 (loop blocks):\n215\t- Loop execution in `workflow-engine.ts` iterates until pass, max-iterations, or circuit-breaker\n216\t- The engine already checks `circuit_breaker.triggered` at line 651 — this story makes that check meaningful by actually setting `triggered: true`\n217\t\n218\tFrom story 1-3 (workflow state):\n219\t- `WorkflowState` includes `circuit_breaker: CircuitBreakerState` with `triggered`, `reason`, `score_history`\n220\t- `EvaluatorScore` includes `iteration`, `passed`, `failed`, `unknown`, `total`, `timestamp`\n221\t- State is persisted as YAML in `.codeharness/workflow-state.yaml`\n222\t\n223\t### Git Intelligence\n224\t\n225\tRecent commits follow the pattern: `feat: story {key} -- {description}`. Each story adds one module file, one test file, and modifies integration points. The codebase uses TypeScript with ESM imports (`.js` extension in import paths).\n226\t\n227\t### References\n228\t\n229\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics-v2.md#Story 7.1: Score-Based Circuit Breaker Module]\n230\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-v2.md#AD1: Module Boundaries — circuit-breaker]\n231\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-v2.md#Implementation Patterns & Consistency Rules]\n232\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-v2.md#Integration Boundaries & Data Flow]\n233\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/prd-evaluator-redesign.md#FR32-35 (Progress & Circuit Breaker)]\n234\t- [Source: src/lib/workflow-state.ts — EvaluatorScore, CircuitBreakerState, WorkflowState types]\n235\t- [Source: src/lib/workflow-engine.ts — loop execution, score recording (lines 587-655)]\n236\t- [Source: src/lib/verdict-parser.ts — EvaluatorVerdict interface]\n237\t- [Source: src/lib/evaluator.ts — evaluator dispatch and result types]\n238\t- [Source: _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/6-3-evaluator-prompt-template.md — predecessor story]\n